# UI test patterns

## Page Object Model (coming)

Page objects will live in `tests/ui-tests/pages/`. One class per page. Each method represents one user-visible action or assertion.

```
tests/ui-tests/
  pages/
    HomePage.ts
    LoginPage.ts
    ArticlePage.ts
    EditorPage.ts
    ProfilePage.ts
  smokeUItest.spec.ts
  *.spec.ts
```

### Page object template

```ts
import { Page, Locator } from '@playwright/test'

export class LoginPage {
  readonly page: Page
  readonly emailInput: Locator
  readonly passwordInput: Locator
  readonly signInButton: Locator

  constructor(page: Page) {
    this.page = page
    this.emailInput = page.getByRole('textbox', { name: 'Email' })
    this.passwordInput = page.getByRole('textbox', { name: 'Password' })
    this.signInButton = page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Sign in' })
  }

  async goto() {
    await this.page.goto('/login')
  }

  async login(email: string, password: string) {
    await this.emailInput.fill(email)
    await this.passwordInput.fill(password)
    await this.signInButton.click()
  }
}
```

### Page object rules

- **Locators are class properties** — defined in the constructor, not inline in methods.
- **Methods encapsulate actions** — one method = one user action or step. Tests call methods, not raw locators.
- **No assertions in page objects** — assertions stay in specs. Page objects only interact.
- **Use `getByRole`, `getByLabel`, `getByText`** for locators — prefer semantic selectors over CSS/XPath.

## UI spec template

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test'
import { LoginPage } from './pages/LoginPage'

test('user can sign in', async ({ page }) => {
  const loginPage = new LoginPage(page)
  await loginPage.goto()
  await loginPage.login(process.env.DEV_USERNAME!, process.env.DEV_PASSWORD!)
  await expect(page.getByRole('button', { name: 'New Article' })).toBeVisible()
})
```

## API-assisted UI tests

For tests that need data already in the system (e.g. an article to view), use Playwright's `request` fixture in `beforeEach` or `test.beforeAll` to set up state via the API — do not drive the UI just to create prerequisites.

```ts
test.beforeEach(async ({ request }) => {
  // create article via API so UI test can find it
  await request.post('https://conduit-api.bondaracademy.com/api/articles', {
    headers: { Authorization: authToken },
    data: { article: { title: '...', description: '...', body: '...' } },
  })
})
```

Or reuse `createToken` and `RequestHandler` directly for full framework consistency.

## Locator strategy — preference order

1. `getByRole` — most resilient to UI changes
2. `getByLabel` — for form fields
3. `getByText` — for visible text
4. `getByTestId` — if `data-testid` attributes are added
5. CSS selector — last resort

## Config

UI base URL comes from `playwright.config.ts` → `use.baseURL` (set from `config.ui.baseURL`). Use relative paths in `page.goto()`:

```ts
await page.goto('/')          // https://conduit.bondaracademy.com/
await page.goto('/login')     // https://conduit.bondaracademy.com/login
```

## Run UI tests

```bash
npx playwright test --project=ui-testing          # headless
npx playwright test --project=ui-testing --headed  # see the browser
npx playwright test --project=ui-testing --debug   # step through with inspector
```
